WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.409 --> 00:00:03.409
&gt;&gt;Marco: Good afternoon.

00:00:03.409 --> 00:00:04.850
Hello, I'm Marco Tempest.

00:00:04.850 --> 00:00:07.840
Thank you very much for coming to my short
presentation.

00:00:07.840 --> 00:00:11.830
I am a cyber illusionist.

00:00:11.830 --> 00:00:16.930
And today I'm going to show you some of the
secrets behind creating magic.

00:00:16.930 --> 00:00:18.390
Cyber illusionist, what does that mean?

00:00:18.390 --> 00:00:23.330
It means I combine magic and science to create
illusions.

00:00:23.330 --> 00:00:28.710
Arthur C. Clark said that "any sufficiently
advanced technology is indistinguishable from

00:00:28.710 --> 00:00:29.710
magic."

00:00:29.710 --> 00:00:35.210
That is true and we magicians have known this
for over two thousand years.

00:00:35.210 --> 00:00:42.899
Around 150 BC, Hero of Alexandria described
how the temples of Ancient Greece were filled

00:00:42.899 --> 00:00:44.640
with magic.

00:00:44.640 --> 00:00:49.950
Others burst into flames.

00:00:49.950 --> 00:00:55.010
Door mysteriously opened.

00:00:55.010 --> 00:00:58.790
Musical instruments played as if touched by
the gods.

00:00:58.790 --> 00:01:04.059
Hero, a mathematician, also explained how
these miracles were accomplished.

00:01:04.059 --> 00:01:09.860
They were all magic tricks--applications of
the little-known sciences of hydraulics, pneumatics,

00:01:09.860 --> 00:01:11.700
and chemistry.

00:01:11.700 --> 00:01:13.400
But to the temple visitors, this was magic.

00:01:13.400 --> 00:01:17.979
Now, magic as an entertainment form has long
separated itself from the gods and superstition,

00:01:17.979 --> 00:01:23.229
but it has always maintained its relationship
with science.

00:01:23.229 --> 00:01:27.250
Magicians are somewhat the original early
adapters of technology.

00:01:27.250 --> 00:01:33.030
Whenever we hear about a new development in
science, whether it's physics, optics, chemistry,

00:01:33.030 --> 00:01:38.760
or even psychology, we figure out ways to
use it in our magic, keeping one step ahead

00:01:38.760 --> 00:01:44.190
of the public and following Arthur C. Clarke's
dictum, "in disguising science as magic."

00:01:44.190 --> 00:01:47.980
Magic that we now accept as part of the world
of entertainment.

00:01:47.980 --> 00:01:50.899
Now, magic is a very introverted field.

00:01:50.899 --> 00:01:55.560
While scientists regularly publish their latest
research, we magicians do not like to share

00:01:55.560 --> 00:01:57.020
our methods and secrets.

00:01:57.020 --> 00:01:59.220
That's true even amongst peers.

00:01:59.220 --> 00:02:06.260
But if we look at creative practice as a form
of research, or art as a form of R and D for

00:02:06.260 --> 00:02:12.240
humanity, then how could a cyber illusionist
like myself share his research?

00:02:12.240 --> 00:02:16.000
Now my own specialty is combining digital
technology and magic.

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:22.140
And it's about three years ago, I started
an exercise in openness and inclusiveness

00:02:22.140 --> 00:02:28.360
by reaching out into the Open Source software
community to create new digital tools for

00:02:28.360 --> 00:02:33.570
magic--tools that could eventually be shared
with its other artists to start them off further

00:02:33.570 --> 00:02:37.730
along in the process and to get them to the
poetry faster.

00:02:37.730 --> 00:02:40.910
I'd like to share with you something that
came out of these collaborations.

00:02:40.910 --> 00:02:46.110
It's augmented reality projection tracking
and mapping system.

00:02:46.110 --> 00:02:47.240
And I brought it with me.

00:02:47.240 --> 00:02:49.870
So, let's have some fun with it.

00:02:49.870 --> 00:02:54.790
