00:08:56.769 --> 00:09:02.580
It may be worth saying something at this point
about the nature of magic.

00:09:02.580 --> 00:09:03.580
What is magic?

00:09:03.580 --> 00:09:06.100
And why do magic tricks fool us?

00:09:06.100 --> 00:09:09.769
Now, magicians are often thought of as being
masters of sleight of hand.

00:09:09.769 --> 00:09:13.050
The quickness of the hands deceives the eye.

00:09:13.050 --> 00:09:14.540
But that is not true.

00:09:14.540 --> 00:09:16.980
Magic does not depend on deceiving the eye.

00:09:16.980 --> 00:09:19.399
It depends on deceiving the brain.

00:09:19.399 --> 00:09:22.390
The tricks of magicians are not designed to
fool the eye.

00:09:22.390 --> 00:09:25.230
The eye observes whatever is put in front
of it.

00:09:25.230 --> 00:09:28.949
It's the brain that translates the scene into
information.

00:09:28.949 --> 00:09:31.899
And the brain loves to look for patterns in
the environment.

00:09:31.899 --> 00:09:37.600
The brain recognizes elements and assumes
that the things he sees now are exactly the

00:09:37.600 --> 00:09:39.699
same as the things he has seen before.

00:09:39.699 --> 00:09:45.579
Now we magicians take advantage of the brain's
lazy thinking because in a magic trick, nothing

00:09:45.579 --> 00:09:47.920
is ever as it seems.

00:09:47.920 --> 00:09:53.050
Magicians carefully design their tricks so
everything about them seems familiar.

00:09:53.050 --> 00:09:54.459
The props seem ordinary.

00:09:54.459 --> 00:09:57.100
The magicians actions above suspicion.

00:09:57.100 --> 00:10:00.949
Even the words we use seems straight-forward
and unambiguous.

00:10:00.949 --> 00:10:04.790
But this veneer of ordinariness covers many
deceptions.

00:10:04.790 --> 00:10:09.679
So, the eye sees everything, but the brain
is being fooled.

